member.remarks:
It is intended to be used in scenarios where a set of tasks are not created in a single function block
like in the example below. 

This is typical for game applications where  is called by the game loop
for every frame to batch multiple 's created on various places. 


// Common task processing
var articles = client.articles.QueryAll();
var orders   = client.orders.QueryAll();
await client.SyncTasks(); 
foreach (var article in articles) { ... }
foreach (var order in orders) { ... }

Message/command methods can be added directly to a  sub class.
When adding many methods it can cause confusion between  own methods and the message/command methods.
The intention is to use a sub class of  as a field in a class extending .
This establish differentiation between  own methods and message/command methods added
to a  sub class.

public class TestStore : FlioxClient
{
    // --- commands
    public MyCommands test;

    public TestStore(FlioxHub hub) : base(hub) {
        test = new MyCommands(this);
    }
}

public class MyCommands : HubMessages
{
    public MyCommands(FlioxClient client) : base(client) { }

    public CommandTask <string> Cmd (string param) => send.Command <string, string>(param);
}

member.summary:
Add a synchronous message handler method with a method signature like:

void TestMessage(Param<string> param, MessageContext context) { ... }

message handler methods can be static or instance methods.

Add an asynchronous message handler method with a method signature like:

Task TestMessage(Param<TestCommand> param, MessageContext context) { ... }

message handler methods can be static or instance methods.

Add a synchronous command handler method with a method signature like:

bool TestCommand(Param<TestCommand> param, MessageContext context) { ... }

command handler methods can be static or instance methods.

Add an asynchronous command handler method with a method signature like:

Task<bool> TestCommand(Param<TestCommand> param, MessageContext context) { ... }

command handler methods can be static or instance methods.

member.remarks:
Additional to commands a class implementing can also be used to declare message handler methods. E.g.
[MessageHandler] void MyMessage(Param<TParam> param, MessageContext context) { }
Note: Message handler methods - in contrast to command handlers - doesn't return a result.
